I think your problem is you&#39;re getting the `sample/register` for both tests.
Please note the tests are not executed right away in a synchronous manner. You&#39;re registering them only (so passing a callback to the `it` method).

Your preparing code is executed right away before any test is executed.

In order to prepare the test scenario you need to use `beforeAll` function that is executed just before any test inside specific `describe`.

```
describe(&#39;GET Request&#39;, () =&gt; {
   let args;
   beforeAll(() =&gt; {
     // an object as you your case is to pass multiple argument
     args = { url: `sample/all` } 
   })
   testCase.validateResponseCode(&#39;get&#39;, () =&gt; args);
});

```

Note that the `args` are not passed by reference but only getter.
You need to apply some small change to the `validateResponseCode` so it calls the getter in order to get the `args` variable.
```
validateResponseCode(requestMethod, argsGetter) {
  it(`RESPONSE CODE VALIDATION: (...) ${requestMethod}`, async () =&gt; {
    // now, this returns the expected values.
    const args = argsGetter(); 
    let response;
    // (...)

 ```

-----

The other (a bit larger refactor) solution would be to use a function factory so you can create scoped `validateResponseCode` function like:

```
const createScopedValidateResponse = (args) =&gt;
  (method) =&gt; testCase.validateResponseCode(method, args);

// usage
const validateResponseCode = createScopedValidateResponse({ url: &#39;url&#39; });

validateResponseCode(&#39;get&#39;);
validateResponseCode(&#39;post&#39;);

```

