I would like to extend an existing JavaScript library which already exists as a global variable.

That library may principally be described as a factory function with additional properties:

```
declare function existingLib ():any
declare namespace existingLib {
// additional classes, functions, properties
}
```
I would now like to add some more stuff to this (already existing) namespace:
```
namespace existingLib {
  export const a = &#39;test&#39; // just as an example
}
```
But, unfortunately, the compiler always creates a local variable `existingLib` which shadows the global one with the same name (which may easily be verified using the TypeScript Playground):
```
&quot;use strict&quot;;
var existingLib;
(function (existingLib) {
    existingLib.a = &#39;test&#39;; // just as an example
})(existingLib || (existingLib = {}));
```
How should my code look like in order to properly extend my library? Shouldn&#39;t `declare function existingLib` be sufficient tell the compiler that there already exists an &quot;external&quot; variable which should not be overwritten/shadowed?

Thanks in advance for any help!

**Outcome:**

With the help of Titian Cernicova-Dragomir it turned out, that TypeScript seems to assume code declaring namespaces to run in a global environment - thus, the &quot;extra&quot; `var` declaration may safely be inserted in order to avoid potential ReferenceErrors because of a missing global variable `existingLib`.

In my case, however, the packaging process surrounded the compiler output by an IIFE (in order to avoid pollution of the global namespace) - which made the extra `var` local and shadowed the actual global variable with the same name. The solution was to &quot;inject&quot; the global `existingLib` as an argument into the IIFE - now, the extra `var` statement is simply ignored and does not cause any harm any longer...

Many thanks to Titian for his ideas which finally led me to that solution!

